{
  "doc_id": "23102",
  "text": "While quantum entanglement is one of the most important resources for quantum technologies, several quantum technological applications are not based on the presence of entanglement, but require other types of nonclassicality. An important example is quantum coherence, which arises from superposition principle of quantum mechanics. In the last years a full resource theory of quantum coherence has been developed [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , which allows for rigorous investigation of coherence for quantum technological tasks, including such fundamental applications as quantum algorithms [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and quantum metrology [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
